@Steve L 

Ugh. 

Or should I say “ough.”

@Kurt 

I guess you have to hold onto it because you don't want it to fall on the ground. I would have preferred "take off" but that doesn't fit 15x15.

Happy 4th everybody!

@Spelling Marauder It would look like

   O h i o

which does look like tractor (facing east): small tires in front, big tires in back.

@Michael 

I live in one of five BOROUGHS of New York City. It is most definitely not just a British word. And it is most definitely pronounced as the puzzle intended. 

New York City also is home to one of the world's greatest fireworks displays, the Macy's Fourth of July extravaganza. 🎵 Bombs bursting in air! 🎶

@Patrick 
C'mon, Patrick, if you don't pick on our  (expletive) puzzles, we won't pick on yours.



🦘🦘🦘🦘🦘 (Emu, you've seen these before.)

@Patrick. Make that unfilled (…auto correct caught me)


.

.

@Fact Boy 
"Open your mouth, the plane is coming in for a landing. Zoooom, and into the hangar." 

Even works with emu food.

@Bill 

I too appreciated that they used “Saddle” and would have liked to have seen “Derailleur.”

It hadn’t occurred to me before that the words you find in Strands look like bike chains, but they do!

@Eric Hougland 

Thanks, Eric. We were killing time on Nauset* beach yesterday, playing 20 questions.  The answer was “poetry.” They had narrowed it down to one of the arts and the question was “is it more like music than painting?” My answer was “yes, definitely.”  This is a great example.

*I’ll bet David C. could tell us that the Nauset were neighbors of the Wampanoag, like them spoke Massachusett (another name for which is Natick!), and were among the first native Americans to have the pleasure of meeting Europeans washing up on the eastern shore, along with their ship’s diseased rats. Some of these people were immediately captured and sold into slavery.  Still, they befriended and helped the immigrants, even siding with them during “King Philip’s” War. (Warning: this episode of Schoolhouse Rock—History is illegal in the state of Florida.  If you’re from Florida and got this far, please unread it.)

@Ann 

Those flavors don’t sound appetizing, do they?

But at least “Oreo” didn’t fit.

@Gig 
So are you saying Orson Wells got it wrong, and he should've pronounced the protaganist's name as 'can' (or maybe 'kahn'?) in "Citizen Kane"?

I know the spelling of proper names can be somewhat arbitrary, but if you spell it 'kane', with an 'e' at the end, you have to expect that most people will say "Spo-kain".

@Lewis 
Yes, I too thank you for pointing out the unique symmetry of this grid.  I’ve been making it a point to try to study the grid patterns before starting my solve, but I overlooked this today. Plenty of grids have had up-down symmetry as well as right-left symmetry, but as you point out, this is only the fifth with purely the former.  Three like this appeared in 2017 and the first appeared in 4/15/2012 by Kevin G. Der. I suggest anyone with a bit of spare time today (or some other day) take a look at that remarkable piece of work. First, it is a massive Sunday, fully  17 x 31.  Secondly, the constructor posted a very detailed account of how this puzzle was imagined and created which is really worth a read. A very unique puzzle from many angles. See:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/5f39s27z" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/5f39s27z</a>

@Captain Obvious 

It would have been just as easy to clue BOROUGH to the five that are in NYC, or if you're aiming for more obscure, it can be a small municipality in New Jersey.  No real reason to bring up this debate by using London.

That said, I don't think the clue was against the rules, just not the best possible one.

@Amy 

“Hearing” is indeed the key word. It’s common in cryptic puzzles, where it means a homophone. 

Once you key into that fact, the puzzle makes sense. I think most of those complainers who didn’t key into that missed the theme because of that.

@Deb 

Thanks.
Happy to hear from you .  I so enjoy your contributions.

@Helen Wright 

Supposedly, the H is the seat and the I is the upright exhaust pipe.  The tractor faces right because the rear tire/tyre is usually larger. 

Hope that helps.

@Helen Wright 

PSA = Public Service Announcement, so that' For Your Information. PSAs are informative bits, usually aired at no or little cost, since they're for the public benefit.

If you look at "oHio" or "OHio" you kind of get the side silhouette of a farm tractor (depending on the size of the wheels).

@Pat 

Go to xwordinfo.com. On the left side of the home page, you can enter the date for any NYT crossword. The page for the puzzle will have a link to the appropriate Wordplay column. 

But since that doesn’t seem to be working well today, here you go: <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/07/07/crosswords/daily-puzzle-2020-07-08.html" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/2020/07/07/crosswords/daily-puzzle-2020-07-08.html</a>

@Deb Amlen 

I find your comment very a-peel-ing, Deb! You really got to the core of the issue and it's nice to know that you and I seed eye to eye on Honeycrisps!

Appleoligies, this was really some low hanging pun fruit but I couldn't resist! 😉

@Healz 

Congrats!

Don't worry about how easy or how hard a lot of prima donnas think this puzzle was.

@Andy 

Visually oHIo is how I saw it. I saw it immediately after I read the clue. It's really clever, isn't it?



emus saw it too.

@Gig And I have been trying to figure out how I knew the pronunciation, having not been there till age 68 and that only passing through.  I spelled it just now for spouse and HE said KAIN. Maybe I heard it on radio or TV once. 
  just strange. 
  Thumbs up for the puzzle! I did try get something like HANDSONHEART to work as the theme, but otherwise smooth sailing.
